ictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>braz</i>, <i>brace</i>, <i>brase</i> ‘arm’, probably used of someone with a strong arm or with a deformity of the arm."],"variants":[{"name":"Brass","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Birse in Aberdeenshire, metathesized to <i>Brass</i>.","English (Northumberland): variant of   Brace  .","North German: nickname from Middle Low German <i>brās</i> ‘noise, pomp’, a related form of <i>brāsch</i> (see   Braasch  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Braci was born in 1225, in Madresfield, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Braci, was 27 and his mother, Maude de Warren (aka Blauminster), was -10. He married Maude De Warenne about 1250. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1289, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 64, and was buried in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1225–1289":"1225–1289","1230–1289":"1230–1289","1257–1317":"8.jaanuar1257kuni7.jaanuar1258–1317","1198–1220":"1198–1220","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1225":"1225","1257":"8. jaanuar 1257 kuni 7. jaanuar 125